defaultDear Mr. Schulz,
defaultWe are very concerned by the assertions in para 5, of the Motion proposed by Mr. Prodi, 
defaulton a 
defaultEuropean strategy on plastic waste in the environment (2013/2113(INI))
default 
defaultwhich was accepted on 27
defaultth
default November in the Environment Committee of the Parliament, and is expected to be voted in Plenary on 13
defaultth
default January.
default&#xa0;
defaultParagraph 5 is defamatory of our members and
default their products, and is an unjustified attack on a whole industry which employs very many people.  Members of the Parliament should not be allowed to use their parliamentary protection from legal action to 
defaultcommit defamation, and it is for that reason that 
defaultwe are bringing this to your attention as President.
default  I trust that Members will have the opportunity to reconsider this ill-advised paragraph in Plenary, and to consider a motion to amend it which I understand will be made.
defaultThere is no evidence that oxo-bi
defaultodegradable plastic is ‘dangerous’ nor that it is ‘disruptive to human health’ or the environment, nor that it contains heavy metals. 
defaultT
defaulthe scientific evidence
default 
defaultis
default that oxo-biodegradable plastic 
default(as distinct from bio-based plastic) 
defaultdoes not
default make recycling pr
defaultocesses more difficult
default. 
defaultThese claims, which are central to the Motion, are false and seriously misleading.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is no evidence in the Commission’s Green Paper on plastic waste in the environment to support these allegations
defaultIn 
defaultFebruary 2011 a Life Cycle
default Assessment
default by Intertek was published by the UK Environment Agency which shows that oxo-biodegradable plastic bags have a better LCA than paper bags or compostable plastic bags.  In May 2012 a further LCA by Intertek
default included the litter metric and compar
defaulted oxo-biodegradable plastic with bio-based plastic and conventional plastic.  It put oxo ahead in its potential to reduce the plastic waste problem and its less harmful impact on the environment and on global warming.    In its ability to reduce plastic l
defaultitter, oxo-bio scored 75% better than conventional plastic, and bio-based plastics were worse than oxo in all 11 environmental impact categories.
default&#xa0;
defaultOxo-biodegradation causes the plastic to convert at the end of its useful life in the presence of oxygen into
default a biodegradable material.  
defaultThis process has been studied in depth at the Technical Research Institute of Sweden and the Swedish University of Agricultural Scienc
defaultes, and a
default peer-reviewed report of the work was published in Vol
default.
default 96 of the journal of Polymer 
defaultDegradation &amp; Stability (2011) at page 919-928.  It shows 91% biodegradation in a soil environment within 24 months, in accordance with ISO 17556
default and it does NOT therefore leave fragments of plastic in the environment. The fragments found in the oceans, an
defaultd those found to have been ingested by birds and fish are fragments of ordinary plastic.
default&#xa0;
defaultOxo-biodegradable plastic does NOT contain heavy metals.  It is designed so that it will NOT degrade in anaerobic conditions and will NOT therefore generate methane.
default&#xa0;
defaultThere is no justification for the claim that ox
defaulto-biodegradable plastics should 
defaultbe phased out of the market or banned outright, as soon as possible before 2020 or at all.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultYours sincerely,
default&#xa0;
